=== W3C [http://www.w3.org/2013/data/ Data Activity] ===
Works to facilitate potentially Web-scale data integration and processing. It does this by providing standard data exchange formats, models, tools, and guidance.

LD4LT will promote awareness of [http://www.w3.org/2013/dwbp/wiki/Main_Page#Best_Practices best practice] from the Data Activity and standardised vocabularies (e.g. [http://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-dcat/ DCAT], [http://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-org/ ORG], [http://www.w3.org/TR/prov-o/ PROV]) from the W3C to identify further language-specific use cases and vocabularies that may be advanced in collaboration with other groups, e.g. [http://www.w3.org/community/bpmlod/ BP-MLOD].

=== W3C [http://www.w3.org/International/ Internationalization Activity] ===
Works with W3C working groups and liaises with other organizations to make it possible to use Web technologies with different languages, scripts, and cultures. It includes the [http://www.w3.org/International/its/ig/ ITS Interest Group], which is maintaining an RDF vocabulary for text annotation based on the [http://www.w3.org/TR/its20/ Internationalization Tag Set 2.0]. 

LD4LT will promote awareness of existing guidelines and best practice promoted in relation to web content, and also assist in identifying use cases needing best practice in interlinking multilingual web and linguistic linked data, and promote these via the BP-MLOD Community Group.

=== Past collaborations === 

In its founding era, LD4LT has been collaborating with W3C [http://www.w3.org/community/sentiment/ Linked Data Models for Emotion and Sentiment Analysis Community Group], but this group went inactive since 2020

